a:260:{i:0;a:1:{s:2:"id";s:19:"2391230524518713479";}i:1;a:1:{s:10:"short_code";s:11:"CEvW34mAkiH";}i:2;a:1:{s:12:"created_time";i:1599276923;}i:3;a:1:{s:7:"caption";s:1652:"So many things have changed for me as I‚Äôve grown older. In my twenties everything seemed like it had to be done now! I spent a fair amount of time at Uni back then and was full steam into educating myself and becoming a better person. ‚Å†
‚Å†
My thirties was having babies and solidifying mycareer‚Ä¶ it was also the decade where burnout was ever looming‚Ä¶ three kids under 5 and multiple startups kept me on my toes.. But also made me cranky and I certainly didn‚Äôt feel like I was doing all the things at 100% all the time.‚Å†
‚Å†
But then I hit 40 and I started to really evaluate my priorities. I started to think about what I valued the most.. And I actually knew that now was the time that I ended to make some hard calls on what I spent my time doing.‚Å†
‚Å†
It wasn‚Äôt enough to do all the things! I had to choose. I had to make a dedicated plan to ensure that I didn‚Äôt look back in another ten years time and regret spending -time on the wrong things.‚Å†
‚Å†
Life audits are tough. You might come to realise that you‚Äôve been spending far too long on things that actually provide little real value to you in terms of your goals‚Ä¶ or your long term future‚Ä¶ but done right, completing a life audit can open up a whole lot of doors that you never knew were available to you.‚Å†
‚Å†
